      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="NA173-kiḷavi">1. itu tōḻi talaivik kuraippāḷāyc ciṟaippuṟamākac colliyatu.
            2. veṟi yaccuṟīit tōḻi yaṟattoṭu nilai payappittatūumām.</p>
        <p xml:lang="en">1. This is what the confidante said as one who is talking to HER while [HE] was behind the fence. 2. It is also how the confidante makes [her] agree to standing up to virtue (~ revealing the truth) by making [her] fear the Veṟi dance.</p>
      </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="NA173">
<l>            cuṉaippūk kuṟṟun toṭalai taiiyu</l>
<l>            malaicceṅ kāntaṭ kaṇṇi tantun</l>
<l>            taṉvaḻip paṭūu nannayan taruḷi</l>
<l>            veṟiyeṉa vuṇarnta variya vaṉṉaiyaik</l>
<l>            kaṇṇiṉuṅ kaṉaviṉuṅ kāṭṭi yinnō </l>
<l>            yeṉṉiṉum vārātu maṇiyiṟ ṟōṉṟu</l>
<l>            mammalai kiḻavōṉ ceytaṉa ṉituveṉiṟ</l>
<l>            paṭuvaṇ ṭārkkum paintār māṟpi</l>
<l>            ṉeṭuvēṭ kēta muṭaittō</l>
<l>            toṭiyōy kūṟumati viṉavuval yāṉē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>Even if we(?) talk of this pain, [and] show mother by eye [or] in a dream</l>
<l rend="indent2">the difficulties, who had realised “[it is time for] the Veṟi dance”,</l>
<l>he<note place="foot">Here we have once more one of these sections where syntax is nearly unmarked, and the message is consequently uncertain. T.V.G. explains the gist to be that <term xml:lang="ta">Murukaṉ</term>, in spite of being worshipped by the girls, does not help them to inform the mother of HER lover and thus avoid the exorcism ceremony. This would explain the use of the neuter finite verb form <term xml:lang="ta">vārātu</term>, which goes with <term xml:lang="ta">muruku</term>, but the possibility, perhaps even the poetic intention, of an alternative version should not be excluded, namely that she directly speaks about the lover.</note> does not come,</l>
<l rend="indent">being favorable(?)<note place="foot">What does it mean when a deity desires (<term xml:lang="ta">naya</term>) a human? There is at least one close parallel in KT 52.2, where SHE is said to be <term xml:lang="ta">cūr nacaintu</term>.</note> [and] granting grace to us who are reverencing him,</l>
<l rend="indent2">plucking flowers in the mountain pool and knitting garlands</l>
<l rend="indent2">and giving chaplets of red Malabar-lilies from the mountain.</l>
<l rend="indent">“The lord of that mountain which appears like a sapphire has done this”,</l>
<l>if he said so, would it afflict the great Vēḷ</l>
<l rend="indent2">with a chest with fresh garlands on which moving(?) bees are humming?</l>
<l>O you with bracelets, speak! I ask [you].</l>
<lg type="alternate">
<l>Even if you talk of this pain, HE does not come,</l>
<l rend="indent2">	being devoted [and] considerate to us who are meeting him,</l>
...
<l>“The lord of that mountain which appears like a sapphire has done it”</l>
<l>– if I say this, conveys it the cause of [your] long desire</l>
<l rend="indent">	for [his] chest with fresh garlands on which moving(?) bees are humming?</l>
<l>O you with bracelets, speak! I ask [you].</l>
</lg>
        </lg>
         </div>
          </body>
